      "content": "My apologies for the confusion earlier. Let's get down to the nitty-gritty, or should I say, the \"goblin-proof\" details. To ensure your tomato plants can absorb the nitrogen they need, you might want to consider using a balanced, slow-release fertilizer with an N-P-K ratio of 10-10-10. This means it contains equal parts nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium, which are essential for plant growth.\n\nAs for the soil pH, tomato plants prefer a slightly acidic to neutral pH, ideally between 6.0 and 6.8. You can test your soil's pH using a simple testing kit available at most garden centers. If the pH is too high (too alkaline), you can lower it by adding sulfur or aluminum sulfate. If it's too low (too acidic), you can raise it by adding lime. Just remember, even the most stubborn goblins can be tamed with the right approach, and your plants will thank you for it!",
